 Let's consider the sum $S$ of the integers from $-25$ to $n$, where $n$ is an integer. We can write this sum as a telescoping series:

\begin{align*}
S &= (-25) +(-24) + \dots + (-2) + (-1) + 0 + 1 + \dots + {k} + \dots + n
\end{align*}

Breaking the sum into cases, we see that

\begin{align*}
-S &= ( 25 + 24 + \dots + k + \dots + n ) \text{ if } n = k \\
-S &= ( 25 + 24 + \dots + k + \dots -k ) \text{ if } n = k-1
\end{align*}

Since $S$ must be at least $26$, $k = 5$ suffices to give

\begin{align*}
26 &\leq \sum_{i=-25}^{k} i \\
&= \sum_{i=-25}^{-k} i
\end{align*}

because the smallest integer in this range is $-k$. This yields $S = 26$ with $k = 5$.
Answer: $\boxed{5}$

